description:
Pacific Forktail, Ischnura cervula

In case you are wondering the male is the blue one. Male damselflies must transfer sperm from their primary genitalia (which are located towards the end of their abdomens) to their secondary, or accessory genitalia (which are near the front of the abdomen). Incredibly, they can do this w in hilst still clasping the female with the end of their abdomen.

description: A Great Basin Fence lizard... on a fence.  Go figure!

East Topanga Fire Road, Pacific Palisades, CA. 

Super fun encounter. Saw this lizard posing impressively by the side of the fire road and stopped to observe. As I stood very still, the lizard approached me, eventually hopping onto my boot and then scrambling up my leg. 

Eventually, after we'd taken some photos and the lizard kept climbing higher, I decided it was time to encourage it to climb down. I moved my leg a little, but the lizard only climbed higher. I moved my water bottle slowly toward it and eventually the lizard climbed down and hopped off. Still didn't run away, though!
